				<string>: : :  TODO  : : :


--- 
FUTURE (no order):

o Refactor regex to use dictionary

o Populate amazon link with found title rather than searched title

o Add graphs Lexile and ZPD vs. Student

o Refactor input validation/cleaning to step through regex dictionary(s)

o Validate manual input free of foreign characters. Unsure how to define foreign in this context. Deferring until it's understood there's an issue.

o Refactor input validation REGEX for fewer steps. One or two multiple capture grouped REGEXs?

o Refactor menu actions to call button labels and links (items in a nested dictionary) by key in higher level dictionary, instead of iterating a list to find actions &amp; links. Significant potential for performance gain.

o Refactor detail match groups using dictionaries, mapping indexed data to index labels and calling dictionary values from within Choose from List display.

o Complete rewrite using main loop (recursive shortcut invocation) architecture

				<string>

---  Scholastic Reading Counts  ---
Also known as SRC or Reading Counts. A testing program offered by Scholastic and Houghton Mifflin Harcourt to monitor your child's progress in reading and reading comprehension. The program awards students RC! Points for each test with a score of 80% or better. Your teacher may offer prizes based on the RC! Points earned. Parents receive periodic progress reports that help correlate test results to leveled reading systems like Lexile or Guided Reading Level. Student progress in the SRC program can be compared to a leveling system to help provide an overall assesment of a student's reading ability. The SRC reports can also help inform reading choices.



---  Instructional Reading Level  ---
Also know as IRL. The grade level at which a student is at least 80% proficient at recognizing words and comprehending reading material. For example, a student with an IRL of 10.8 would be at least 80% proficient at reading tenth grade words and books.



---  Zone of Proximal Development  ---
Also known as ZPD. The reading level range from which a student should be selecting books for optimal growth in reading.



---  Reading Level  ---
Also known as Grade Equivalent reading level. A quantitative measure, expressed in grade levels, of both a text's difficulty and reader's ability. For example, a book rated 3.1 would be a match for a third grade student towards the beginning of the school year; a 3.5 rating would be appropriate approximately half way through third grade.



---  Guided Reading Level  ---
Also known as GRL or Fountas and Pinnell Levels. A quantitative measure of both a text's difficulty and reader's ability. GRL ranks books from A to Z, with A being easiest. A student's Guided Teading Level is determined through testing, either standardized or title-specific. The GRL method prescribes a range of book rankings by grade level.



---  Lexile  ---
A quantitave measure used to match readers with books. Readers and books are assigned a score on the Lexile scale, in which higher scores reflect more difficult text and higher student reading ability. A student's Lexile level is determined through testing, either standardized or title-specific. Although the score range is not fixed, it is typically 0L-2000+L. Beginning readers may be scored less than 0L.



---  Lexile Prefix Codes  ---
AD (Adult-directed): books typically read to a child

NC (Non-conforming): books with a Lexile measure significantly higher than is typical for the publisher's intended audience

HL (High-Low): Books with a Lexile measure much lower than the average reading ability of the intended age range of its readers

IG (Illustrated Guide): books with non-linear content where reordering content would not affect the flow of the book

GN (Graphic Novel): graphic novel or comic book where the majority of the text appears as voice in thought bubbles

BR (Beginning Reader): books or readers with a Lexile measure below 0L

NP (Non-Prose): book comprising more than 50% non-standard or non-conforming prose, whose text cannot be assigned a Lexile measure
